# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: algorithmic-game-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] In traditional algorithm design, inputs are assumed to be fixed and reliable.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] However, in many real-world applications—such as online auctions, internet routing, digital advertising, and resource allocation systems—inputs are provided by multiple independent agents who may strategically misreport information to manipulate outcomes in their favor.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] AGT provides frameworks to analyze and design systems that remain effective despite such strategic behavior.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] Algorithm designers in this domain must satisfy traditional algorithmic requirements (such as *polynomial-time running time* and *good approximation ratio*) while simultaneously addressing incentive constraints that ensure participants act according to the system's intended design.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] In 1999, the seminal paper of Noam Nisan and Amir Ronen drew the attention of the Theoretical Computer Science community to designing algorithms for selfish (strategic) users.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] This paper coined the term algorithmic mechanism design and was recognized by the 2012 Gödel Prize committee as one of "three papers laying foundation of growth in Algorithmic Game Theory".
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] The other two papers cited in the 2012 Gödel Prize for fundamental contributions to Algorithmic Game Theory introduced and developed the concept of "Price of Anarchy".
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] In their 1999 paper "Worst-case Equilibria", Koutsoupias and Papadimitriou proposed a new measure of the degradation of system efficiency due to the selfish behavior of its agents: the ratio of between system efficiency at an optimal configuration, and its efficiency at the worst Nash equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] The Internet created a new economy—both as a foundation for exchange and commerce, and in its own right.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] The computational nature of the Internet allowed for the use of computational tools in this new emerging economy.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] On the other hand, the Internet itself is the outcome of actions of many.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] This was new to the classic, ‘top-down’ approach to computation that held till then.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] Thus, game theory is a natural way to view the Internet and interactions within it, both human and mechanical.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] Game theory studies equilibria (such as the Nash equilibrium).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] An equilibrium is generally defined as a state in which no player has an incentive to change their strategy.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] Equilibria are found in several fields related to the Internet, for instance financial interactions and communication load-balancing.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] Game theory provides tools to analyze equilibria, and a common approach is then to ‘find the game’—that is, to formalize specific Internet interactions as a game, and to derive the associated equilibria.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] Rephrasing problems in terms of games allows the analysis of Internet-based interactions and the construction of mechanisms to meet specified demands.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] If equilibria can be shown to exist, a further question must be answered: can an equilibrium be found, and in reasonable time?
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] This leads to the analysis of algorithms for finding equilibria.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] Of special importance is the complexity class PPAD, which includes many problems in algorithmic game theory.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] Mechanism design is the subarea of economics that deals with optimization under incentive constraints.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] Algorithmic mechanism design considers the optimization of economic systems under computational efficiency requirements.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] Typical objectives studied include revenue maximization and social welfare maximization.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] The concepts of price of anarchy and price of stability were introduced to capture the loss in performance of a system due to the selfish behavior of its participants.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] The price of anarchy captures the worst-case performance of the system at equilibrium relative to the optimal performance possible.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] The price of stability, on the other hand, captures the relative performance of the best equilibrium of the system.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] These concepts are counterparts to the notion of approximation ratio in algorithm design.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] The existence of an equilibrium in a game is typically established using non-constructive fixed point theorems.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] There are no efficient algorithms known for computing Nash equilibria.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] The problem is complete for the complexity class PPAD even in 2-player games.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] In contrast, correlated equilibria can be computed efficiently using linear programming, as well as learned via no-regret strategies.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] Computational social choice studies computational aspects of *social choice*, the aggregation of individual agents' preferences.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] Examples include algorithms and computational complexity of voting rules and coalition formation.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/algorithmic-game-theory] Algorithmic Game Theory papers are often also published in Game Theory journals such as GEB, Economics journals such as Econometrica, and Computer Science journals such as SICOMP.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] The paradox may have analogies in electrical power grids and biological systems.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] It has been suggested that, in theory, the improvement of a malfunctioning network could be accomplished by removing certain parts of it.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] The paradox has been used to explain instances of improved traffic flow when existing major roads are closed.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Dietrich Braess, a mathematician at Ruhr University, Germany, noticed the flow in a road network could be impeded by adding a new road, when he was working on traffic modelling.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] His idea was that if each driver is making the optimal self-interested decision as to which route is quickest, a shortcut could be chosen too often for drivers to have the shortest travel times possible.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] More formally, the idea behind Braess's discovery is that the Nash equilibrium may not equate with the best overall flow through a network.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Adding extra capacity to a network when the moving entities selfishly choose their route can in some cases reduce overall performance.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] That is because the Nash equilibrium of such a system is not necessarily optimal.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] The network change induces a new game structure which leads to a (multiplayer) prisoner's dilemma.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In a Nash equilibrium, drivers have no incentive to change their routes.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] While the system is not in a Nash equilibrium, individual drivers are able to improve their respective travel times by changing the routes they take.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In the case of Braess's paradox, drivers will continue to switch until they reach Nash equilibrium despite the reduction in overall performance.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] If the latency functions are linear, adding an edge can never make total travel time at equilibrium worse by a factor of more than 4/3.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Braess's paradox has a counterpart in case of a reduction of the road network, which may cause a reduction of individual commuting time.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In Seoul, South Korea, traffic around the city sped up when the Cheonggye Expressway was removed as part of the Cheonggyecheon restoration project.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In Stuttgart, Germany, after investments into the road network in 1969, the traffic situation did not improve until a section of newly built road was closed for traffic again.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In 1990 the temporary closing of 42nd Street in Manhattan, New York City, for Earth Day reduced the amount of congestion in the area.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In 2008 Youn, Gastner and Jeong demonstrated specific routes in Boston, New York City and London where that might actually occur and pointed out roads that could be closed to reduce predicted travel times.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In 2009, New York experimented with closures of Broadway at Times Square and Herald Square, which resulted in improved traffic flow and permanent pedestrian plazas.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In 2012, Paul Lecroart, of the institute of planning and development of the Île-de-France, wrote that "Despite initial fears, the removal of main roads does not cause deterioration of traffic conditions beyond the starting adjustments.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] The traffic transfer are limited and below expectations".
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] He also notes that some private vehicle trips (and related economic activity) are not transferred to public transport and simply disappear ("evaporate").
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] The same phenomenon was also observed when road closing was not part of an urban project but the consequence of an accident.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In 2012 in Rouen, a bridge was destroyed by fire.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Over the next two years, other bridges were used more, but the total number of cars crossing bridges was reduced.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Consider a road network on which 4000 drivers wish to travel from a Start point to an End point.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] They have two roads available to choose from, one that goes via point A and one that goes via point B.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] The travel time in minutes from the Start to point A is the number of travellers (T) divided by 100, and the time to point B is a constant 45 minutes.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] These times are then reversed for the routes to the End point: from point A to the End point takes 45 minutes, and from B to the End point takes ${\tfrac {T}{100}}$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] If these are the only routes available, the time needed to drive Start–A–End route with a drivers would be ${\tfrac {a}{100}}+45$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] The time needed to drive the Start–B–End route with b drivers would be ${\tfrac {b}{100}}+45$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] As there are 4000 drivers, the fact that $a+b=4000$ can be used to derive the fact that $a=b=2000$ when the system is at equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] If either route took less time, it would not be a Nash equilibrium: a rational driver would switch from the longer route to the shorter route.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Now suppose a new road was built connecting points A and B, with an extremely short travel time of approximately 0 minutes.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Suppose that the road is opened and one driver tries Start–A–B–End.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Soon, more of the 4000 drivers are trying this new route.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] The time taken rises from 40.01 and keeps climbing.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] When the number of drivers trying the new route reaches 2500, with 1500 still in the Start–B–End route, their time will be ${\tfrac {2500}{100}}+{\tfrac {4000}{100}}=65$ minutes, which is no improvement over the original route.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Nobody has any incentive to travel A-End or Start-B because any driver trying them will take 85 minutes.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Thus, the opening of the cross route triggers an irreversible change to it by everyone, costing everyone 80 minutes instead of the original 65.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] If every driver were to agree not to use the A–B path, or if that route were closed, every driver would benefit by a 15-minute reduction in travel time.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] If one assumes the travel time for each person driving on an edge to be equal, an equilibrium will always exist.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Let $L_{e}(x)$ be the formula for the travel time of each person traveling along edge e when x people take that edge.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Suppose there is a traffic graph with $x_{e}$ people driving along edge e .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Let the total energy of the traffic graph be the sum of the energies of every edge in the graph.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Take a choice of routes that minimizes the total energy.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Such a choice must exist because there are finitely many choices of routes.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Assume, for contradiction, this is not the case.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Then, there is at least one driver who can switch the route and improve the travel time.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Let E be total energy of the traffic graph, and consider what happens when the route $e_{0},e_{1},...e_{n}$ is removed.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] That is simply the total travel time needed to take the original route.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] If the new route is then added, $e'_{0},e'_{1},\ldots ,e'_{m}$ , the total energy E will be increased by the total travel time needed to take the new route.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Because the new route is shorter than the original route, E must decrease relative to the original configuration, contradicting the assumption that the original set of routes minimized the total energy.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Therefore, the choice of routes minimizing total energy is an equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] The above proof outlines a procedure known as best response dynamics, which finds an equilibrium for a linear traffic graph and terminates in a finite number of steps.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] The algorithm is termed "best response" because at each step of the algorithm, if the graph is not at equilibrium then some driver has a best response to the strategies of all other drivers and switches to that response.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] At each step, if some particular driver could do better by taking an alternate path (a "best response"), doing so strictly decreases the energy of the graph.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] If no driver has a best response, the graph is at equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Since the energy of the graph strictly decreases with each step, the best response dynamics algorithm must eventually halt.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] If the travel time functions are linear, that is $L_{e}(x)=a_{e}x+b_{e}$ for some $a_{e},b_{e}\geq 0$ , then at worst, traffic in the energy-minimizing equilibrium is twice as bad as socially optimal.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Proof: Let Z be some traffic configuration, with associated energy $E(Z)$ and total travel time $T(Z)$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] For each edge, the energy is the sum of an arithmetic progression, and using the formula for the sum of an arithmetic progression, one can show that $E(Z)\leq T(Z)\leq 2E(Z)$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] If $Z_{o}$ is the socially-optimal traffic flow and $Z_{e}$ is the energy-minimizing traffic flow, the inequality implies that $T(Z_{e})\leq 2E(Z_{e})\leq 2E(Z_{o})\leq 2T(Z_{o})$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Thus, the total travel time for the energy-minimizing equilibrium is at most twice as bad as for the optimal flow.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Mlichtaich proved that Braess's paradox occurs in a two-terminal network if and only if it is not a series-parallel graph.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In 1983, Steinberg and Zangwill provided, under reasonable assumptions, the necessary and sufficient conditions for Braess's paradox to occur in a general transportation network when a new route is added.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] (Note that their result applies to the addition of *any* new route, not just to the case of adding a single link.) As a corollary, they obtain that Braess's paradox is about as likely to occur as not occur when a random new route is added.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In 2012, scientists at the Max Planck Institute for Dynamics and Self-Organization demonstrated, through computational modelling, the potential for the phenomenon to occur in power transmission networks where power generation is decentralized.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In 2012, an international team of researchers from Institut Néel (CNRS, France), INP (France), IEMN (CNRS, France) and UCL (Belgium) published in *Physical Review Letters* a paper showing that Braess's paradox may occur in mesoscopic electron systems.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In particular, they showed that adding a path for electrons in a nanoscopic network paradoxically reduced its conductance.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] That was shown both by simulations as well as experiments at low temperature using scanning gate microscopy.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] A model with springs and ropes can show that a hung weight can rise in height despite a taut rope in the hanging system being cut, and follows from the same mathematical structure as the original Braess's paradox.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] For two identical springs joined in series by a short rope, their total spring constant is half of each individual spring, resulting in a long stretch when a certain weight is hung.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] This remains the case as we add two longer ropes in slack to connect the lower end of the upper spring to the hung weight (lower end of the lower spring), and the upper end of the lower spring to the hanging point (upper end of the upper spring).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] However, when the short rope is cut, the longer ropes become taut, and the two springs become parallel (in the mechanical sense) to each other.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] The total spring constant is twice that of each individual spring, and when the length of the long ropes is not too long, the hung weight will actually be higher compared to before the short rope was cut.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] The fact that the hung weight rises despite cutting a taut rope (the short rope) in the hanging system is counter-intuitive, but it does follow from Hooke's law and the way springs work in series and in parallel.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Motter and collaborators demonstrated that Braess's paradox outcomes may often occur in biological and ecological systems.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Motter suggests removing part of a perturbed network could rescue it.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] For resource management of endangered species food webs, in which extinction of many species might follow sequentially, selective removal of a doomed species from the network could in principle bring about the positive outcome of preventing a series of further extinctions.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] A proposed solution for maximum efficiency in scoring is for a star player to shoot about the same number of shots as teammates.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] However, this approach is not supported by hard statistical evidence, as noted in the original paper.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Braess's paradox has been shown to appear in blockchain payment channel networks, also known as layer-2 networks.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Payment channel networks implement a solution to the scalability problem of blockchain networks, allowing transactions of high rates without recording them on the blockchain.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] In such a network, users can establish a channel by locking funds on each side of the channel.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] Transactions are executed either through a channel connecting directly the payer and payee or through a path of channels with intermediate users that ask for some fees.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] While intuitively, opening new channels allows higher routing flexibility, adding a new channel might cause higher fees, and similarly closing existing channels might decrease fees.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/braess-s-paradox] The paper presented a theoretical analysis with conditions for the paradox, methods for mitigating the paradox as well as an empirical analysis, showing the appearance in practice of the paradox and its effects on Bitcoin's Lightning network.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] A **combinatorial auction** is a type of smart market in which participants can place bids on combinations of discrete heterogeneous items, or “packages”, rather than individual items or continuous quantities.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] These packages can be also called lots and the whole auction a **multi-lot auction**.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] Combinatorial auctions are applicable when bidders have non-additive valuations on bundles of items, that is, they value combinations of items more or less than the sum of the valuations of individual elements of the combination.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] Simple combinatorial auctions have been used for many years in estate auctions, where a common procedure is to accept bids for packages of items.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] They have been used recently for truckload transportation, bus routes, industrial procurement, and in the allocation of radio spectrum for wireless communications.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] In recent years, procurement teams have applied reverse combinatorial auctions in the procurement of goods and services.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] This application is often referred to as sourcing optimization.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] Since construction procurement often involves negotiations over multiple components, combinatorial reverse auctions are suggested to reduce costs in this industry.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] Although they allow bidders to be more expressive, combinatorial auctions present both computational and game-theoretic challenges compared to traditional auctions.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] An example of a computational problem is how to efficiently determine the allocation once the bids have been submitted to the auctioneer.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] This is called the winner determination problem.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] The winner determination problem can be stated as follows: given a set of bids in a combinatorial auction, find an allocation of items to bidders—including the possibility that the auctioneer retains some items—that maximizes the auctioneer’s revenue.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] This problem is difficult for large instances.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] Specifically, it is NP-hard, meaning that it is conjectured that there does not exist a polynomial-time algorithm which finds the optimal allocation.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] The combinatorial auction problem can be modeled as a set packing problem.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] Therefore, many algorithms have been proposed to find approximated solutions for combinatorial auction problem.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] For example, Hsieh (2010) proposed a Lagrangian relaxation approach for combinatorial reverse auction problems.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] Many of these aspects of combinatorial auctions, including some real-world examples, are also discussed in the comprehensive book edited by Cramton, Shoham and Steinberg (2006).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] Combinatorial auctions were first proposed by Rassenti, Smith, and Bulfin (1982), for the allocation of airport landing slots.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] A special case of a combinatorial auction is the **combinatorial clock auction** (CCA), which combines a clock auction, during which bidders may provide their confirmations in response to the rising prices, with a subsequent sealed bid auction, in which bidders submit sealed package bids.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] The auctioneer uses the final bids to compute the best value allocation and the Vickrey payments.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/combinatorial-auction] CCAs have been shown to be prone to the possibility of raising rivals’ cost.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The research of congestion games was initiated by the American economist Robert W.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] He proved that every congestion game has a Nash equilibrium in pure strategies (aka *pure Nash equilibrium*, PNE).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] During the proof, he in fact proved that every congestion game is an exact potential game.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Later, Monderer and Shapley proved a converse result: any game with an exact potential function is equivalent to some congestion game.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Consider a traffic net where two players originate at point O and need to get to point T.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Suppose that node O is connected to node T via two paths: *O*-*A*-*T* and *O*-*B*-*T*, where A is a little closer than B (i.e.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] A is more likely to be chosen by each player), as in the picture at the right.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The roads from both connection points to T get easily congested, meaning the more players pass through a point, the greater the delay of each player becomes, so having both players go through the same connection point causes extra delay.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Formally, the delay in each of *A**T* and *B**T* when x players go there is $x^{2}$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] A good outcome in this game will be for the two players to "coordinate" and pass through different connection points.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The pure Nash equilibria in this game are (OAT,OBT) and (OBT,OAT): any unilateral change by one of the players increases the cost of this player (note that the values in the table are costs, so players prefer them to be smaller).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] In this example, the Nash equilibrium is *efficient* - the players choose different lanes and the sum of costs is minimal.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] In contrast, suppose the delay in each of AT and BT when x players go there is $0.8x$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Now, the only pure Nash equilibrium is ⁠ $(OAT,OAT)$ ⁠: any player switching to OBT increases his cost from 2.6 to 2.8.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] An equilibrium still exists, but it is not efficient: the sum of costs is 5.2, while the sum of cost in ⁠ $(OAT,OBT)$ ⁠ and ⁠ $(OBT,OAT)$ ⁠ is 4.6.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The basic definition of a CG has the following components.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Every CG has a Nash equilibrium in pure strategies.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This can be shown by constructing a *potential function* that assigns a value to each outcome.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Moreover, this construction will also show that iterated best response finds a Nash equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Note that this function is *not* the social welfare $\textstyle \sum _{e\in E}x_{e}d_{e}(x_{e})$ , but rather a discrete integral of sorts.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The critical property of a potential function for a congestion game is that if one player switches strategy, the change in his delay is equal to the change in the potential function.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Consider the case when player i switches from $P_{i}$ to $Q_{i}$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Elements that are in both of the strategies remain unaffected, elements that the player leaves (i.e. $e\in P_{i}-Q_{i}$ ) decrease the potential by $d_{e}(x_{e})$ , and the elements the player joins (i.e. $e\in Q_{i}-P_{i}$ ) increase the potential by $d_{e}(x_{e}+1)$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This change in potential is precisely the change in delay for player i, so $\Phi$ is in fact a potential function.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Now observe that any minimum of $\Phi$ is a pure Nash equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Fixing all but one player, any improvement in strategy by that player corresponds to decreasing $\Phi$ , which cannot happen at a minimum.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Now since there are a finite number of configurations and each $d_{e}$ is monotone, there exists an equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The existence of a potential function has an additional implication, called the **finite improvement property (FIP)**.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] If we start with any strategy-vector, pick a player arbitrarily, and let him change his strategy to a better strategy for him, and repeat, then the sequence of improvements must be finite (that is, the sequence will not cycle).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This is because each such improvement strictly increases the potential.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Below we present various extensions and variations on the basic CG model.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] A **nonatomic** **CG** is the limit of a standard CG with *n* players, as $n\rightarrow \infty$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] As in any nonatomic game, there is a continuum of players, the players are considered "infinitesimally small", and each individual player has a negligible effect on the congestion.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Nonatomic CGs were studied by Milchtaich, Friedman, Blonsky, and Roughgarden and Tardos.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Strategies are now collections of strategy profiles $f_{P}$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] For a strategy set $S_{i}$ of size n, the collection of all valid profiles is a compact subset of $[0,r_{i}]^{n}$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] We now define the potential function as $\textstyle \Phi =\sum _{e\in E}\int _{0}^{x_{e}}d_{e}(z)\,dz$ , replacing the discrete integral with the standard one.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] As a function of the strategy, $\Phi$ is continuous: $d_{e}$ is continuous by assumption, and $x_{e}$ is a continuous function of the strategy.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Then by the extreme value theorem, $\Phi$ attains its global minimum.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The final step is to show that a minimum of $\Phi$ is indeed a Nash equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Assume for contradiction that there exists a collection of $f_{P}$ that minimize $\Phi$ but are not a Nash equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Then for some type i, there exists some improvement $Q\in S_{i}$ over the current choice P.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The idea now is to take a small amount $\delta <f_{P}$ of players using strategy P and move them to strategy Q.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Now for any $x_{e}\in Q$ , we have increased its load by $\delta$ , so its term in $\Phi$ is now $\textstyle \int _{0}^{x_{e}+\delta }d_{e}(z)dz$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Differentiating the integral, this change is approximately $\delta \cdot d_{e}(x_{e})$ , with error $\delta ^{2}$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The equivalent analysis of the change holds when we look at edges in P.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Therefore, the change in potential is approximately $\textstyle \delta (\sum _{e\in Q}d_{e}(x_{e})-\sum _{e\in P}d_{e}(x_{e}))$ , which is less than zero.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This is a contradiction, as then $\Phi$ was not minimized.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Therefore, a minimum of $\Phi$ must be a Nash equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] In a **splittable CG** (also called **atomic splittable CG**), as in an atomic CG, there are finitely many players, each of whom has a certain load to transfer.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] As in a nonatomic CG, each player can split his load into fractional loads going through different paths, like a transportation company choosing a set of paths for mass transportation.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] In contrast to a nonatomic CG, each player has a non-negligible effect on the congestion.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Splittable CGs were first analyzed by Ariel Orda, Raphael Rom and Nachum Shimkin in 1993, in the context of communication networks.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] They show that, for a simple network with two nodes and multiple parallel links, the Nash equilibrium is unique under reasonable convexity conditions, and has some interesting monotonicity properties.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] For general network topologies, more complex conditions are required to guarantee the uniqueness of Nash equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] In parallel, Haurie and Marcotte studied splittable CGs in the context of transportation networks.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] They defined a Nash-Cournot equilibrium and provided conditions for its existence and uniqueness.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] They showed that, under reasonable conditions, the asymptotic behavior of this NE yield a total flow vector corresponding to a Wardrop equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The price of anarchy in splittable CGs was studied by Gairing, Monien and Tiemann, Cominetti, Correa and Stier-Moses, Harks, and finally Roughgarden and Schoppmann.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Huang studies the effect of collusion on the social cost in splittable CGs.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] He shows that if the network satifies some natural structural condition, and all delay functions are affine, then collusion decreases the social cost in equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] But if either of these conditions is not satisfied, collusion might decrease the social cost.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Richman and Shimkin characterize the networks that guarantee that every splittable CG has a unique PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Harks and Timmermans also study equilibrium uniqueness in atomic splittable polymatroid CGs.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Marcotte presented four numeric algorithms for computing NE on congested transportation networks, and analyzed their convergence properties.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Meunier and Pradeau presented a numeric algorithm, similar to the Lemke-Howson algorithm, for nonatomic network CGs with affine player-specific delay functions.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Both these numeric algorithms were not shown to run in polynomial time.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Cominetti, Correa and Stier-Moses studied splittable CGs with affine player-independent delay functions: $d_{e,i}(x)=a_{e}\cdot x_{e}+b_{e}$ , where *xe* is the load on edge *e*, and *ae*,*be* are player-independent constants.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] They showed a convex potential function whose global minima are PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This means that epsilon-approximate PNEs can be computed in polytime by convex programming.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Huang also considered affine player-independent delay functions.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] He devised a combinatorial algorithm computing an exact PNE for splittable CGs on symmetric graphs that satisfy a natural structural condition he calls "well-designed" (for example, series–parallel graphs).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Bhaskar and Lolakapuri considered splittable network CGs with convex player-independent delay functions.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] They presented two algorithms for computing approximate PNE: the first is exponential in the number of players, and while the second is exponential in the number of edges.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] They also show that in general networks, it is NP-hard to decide if there exists a PNE where every player has cost at most some given constant *C*.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Klimm and Warode studied atomic splittable network CGs with affine player-specific delay functions $d_{e,i}(x)=a_{e,i}\cdot x_{e}+b_{e,i}$ , where *xe* is the load on edge *e*, and *aei*, *bei* are player-specific constants.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] They proved that computing a PNE is PPAD-complete.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Harks and Timmermans study splittable atomic CGs with singleton strategy sets - each player should split his load among the edges (not among the paths).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This corresponds to a network of *m* parallel edges between the source and the target.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] They allow player-specific delay functions.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The total cost suffered by each player *i* is $\sum _{e}x_{i,e}\cdot d_{e,i}(x)$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] They present an algorithm for computing a PNE in time $O((nm)^{3}+n^{2}m^{14}\log(D/k_{0}))$ , where *n* is the number of players, *m* the number of edges, *D* is the maximum player-specific demand, and *k*0 the smallest packet size.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] They also note that computing a PNE in atomic splittable CGs with singleton strategies and affine delay funcions can be presented as a Linear complementarity problem.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] In a **weighted** **CG**, different players may have different effects on the congestion.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] For example, in a road network, a truck adds congestion much more than a motorcycle.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Whereas an unweighted CG is an anonymous game, a weighted CG is not anonymous, as the payoff of a player depends not only on the number of players who take each action, but also on their weight.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] In general, the weight of a player may depend on the resource (**resource-specific weights**): for every player *i* and resource *e*, there is weight $w_{i,e}$ , and the load on the resource *e* is $x_{e}=\sum _{i:e\in P_{i}}w_{i,e}$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] An important special case is when the weight depends only on the player (**resource-independent weights**), that is, each player i has a weight $w_{i}$ , and $x_{e}=\sum _{i:e\in P_{i}}w_{i}$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Milchtaich considered the special case of weighted CGs in which each strategy is a single resource ("singleton CG"), the weights are *resource-independent*, and all players have the same strategy set.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Milchtaich considered the special case of weighted CGs in which each strategy is a path in a given undirected graph ("network CG").
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] He proved that every finite game can be represented as a weighted network congestion game, with nondecreasing (but not necessarily negative) cost-functions.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This implies that not every such game has a PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Concrete examples of weighted CGs without PNE are given by Libman and Orda, as well as Goemans Mirrokni and Vetta.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This raises the question of what conditions guarantee the existence of PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] In particular, we say that a certain graph *G guarantees* a certain property if every weighted network CG in which the underlying network is *G* has that property.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Milchtaich characterized networks that guarantee the existence of PNE, as well as the finite-improvement property, with the additional condition that a player with a lower weight has weakly more allowed strategies (formally, $w_{i}<w_{j}$ implies $|S_{i}|\geq |S_{j}|$ ).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] In the special case in which every player is allowed to use any strategy ("public edges"), there are more networks that guarantee the existence of PNE; a complete characterization of such networks is posed as an open problem.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Holzman and Law-Yone also characterize the networks that guarantee that every atomic CG has a strong PNE, a unique PNE, or a Pareto-efficient PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Richman and Shimkin characterize the networks that guarantee that every *splittable* CG has a unique PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] We say that a class *C* of functions *guarantees* a certain property if every weighted CG in which all delay functions are elements of *C* has that property.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Gairing, Monien and Tiemann study weighted network CGs with player-specific delays.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] They consider both splittable and unsplittable flows.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] When the delay functions are linear (without a constant term, that is *be*=0), they introduce two new potential functions and derive results on computation of PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] There are many other papers about weighted congestion games.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The basic CG model can be extended by allowing the delay function of each resource to depend on the player.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] So for each resource *e* and player *i*, there is a delay function $d_{i,e}$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Given a strategy $P_{i}$ , player i experiences delay $\textstyle \sum _{e\in P_{i}}d_{i,e}(x_{e})$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This special case of CG is also called a **crowding game**.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] It represents a setting in which several people simultaneously choose a place to go to (e.g. a room, a settlement, a restaurant), and their payoff is determined both by the place and by the number of other players choosing the same place.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] In a crowding game, given a strategy $P_{i}=\{e\}$ , player i experiences delay $d_{i,e}(x_{e})$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] If the player switches to a different strategy f, his delay would be $d_{i,f}(x_{f}+1)$ ; hence, a strategy vector is a PNE iff for every player i, $d_{i,e}(x_{e})\leq d_{i,f}(x_{f}+1)$ for all *e*,*f*.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] In general, CGs with player-specific delays might *not* admit a potential function.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This shows that the finite-improvement property does not hold, so the game cannot have a potential function (not even a generalized-ordinal-potential function).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] When there are three or more players, even best-response paths might be cyclic.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The proof is constructive and shows an algorithm that finds a Nash equilibrium in at most ${n+1 \choose 2}$ steps.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Moreover, every CG is weakly acyclic: for any initial strategy-vector, at least one best-response path starting at this vector has a length of at most $r{n+1 \choose 2}$ , which terminates at an equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Every crowding game is *sequentially solvable*.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This means that, for every ordering of the players, the sequential game in which each player in turn picks a strategy has a subgame-perfect equilibrium in which the players' actions are a PNE in the original simultaneous game.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Every crowding game has at least one strong PNE; every strong PNE of a crowding game can be attained as a subgame-perfect equilibrium of a sequential version of the game.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] In general, a crowding game might have many different PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] For example, suppose there are *n* players and *n* resources, and the negative effect of congestion on the payoff is much higher than the positive value of the resources.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Then there are n! different PNEs: every one-to-one matching of players to resources is a PNE, as no player would move to a resource occupied by another player.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] However, if a crowding game is replicated *m* times, then the set of PNEs converges to a single point as *m* goes to infinity.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Moreover, in a "large" (nonatomic) crowding game, there is generically a unique PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This PNE has an interesting graph-theoretic property.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Let *G* be a bipartite graph with players on one side and resources on the other side, where each player is adjacent to all the resources that his copies choose in the unique PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] A special case of the player-specific delay functions is that the delay functions can be separated into a player-specific factor and a general factor.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] When only pure-strategies are considered, these two notions are equivalent, since the logarithm of a product is a sum.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Moreover, when players may have resource-specific weights, the setting with resource-specific delay functions can be reduced to the setting with a universal delay function.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Games with separable cost functions occur in load-balancing, M/M/1 queueing, and habitat selection.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Every weighted *singleton* CG with separable player-specific preferences is isomorphic to a weighted *network* CG with player-independent preference.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Milchtaich considered the special case of CGs with player-specific costs, in which each strategy is a path in a given graph ("network CG").
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] He proved that every finite game can be represented as an (unweighted) network congestion game with player-specific costs, with nondecreasing (but not necessarily negative) cost-functions.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] A complete characterization of networks that guarantee the existence of PNE in such CGs is posed as an open problem.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The proof of existence of PNE is constructive: it shows a finite algorithm (an improvement path) that always finds a PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This raises the question of how many steps are required to find this PNE?
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Even-Dar, Kesselman and Mansour analyze the number of steps required for convergence to equilibrium in a load-balancing setting.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Caragiannis, Fanelli, Gravin and Skopalik present an algorithm that computes a constant-factor approximation PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Their algorithm identifies a short sequence of best-response moves, that leads to an approximate equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] They also show that, for more general CGs, attaining any polynomial approximation of PNE is PLS-complete.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Fotakis, Kontogiannis and Spirakis present an algorithm that, in any weighted network CG with linear delay functions, finds a PNE in pseudo-polynomial time (polynomial in the number of players *n* and the sum of players' weights *W*).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Their algorithm is a greedy best-response algorithm: players enter the game in descending order of their weight, and choose a best-response to existing players' strategies.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Panagopoulou and Spirakis show empirical evidence that the algorithm of Fotakis, Kontogiannis and Spirakis in fact runs in time polynomial in *n* and log *W*.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] They also propose an initial strategy-vector that dramatically speeds this algorithm.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] In general, a weighted network CG may not have a PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] The proof is by reduction from the directed edge-disjoint paths problem.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Caragiannis, Fanelli, Gravin and Skopalik present an algorithm that computes a constant-factor approximation PNE in weighted CGs.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] To prove their results, they show that, although weighted CGs may not have a potential function, every weighted CG can be *approximated* by a certain potential game.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] This lets them show that every weighted CG has a (*d*!)-approximate PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/congestion-game] Their algorithm identifies a short sequence of best-response moves, that leads to such an approximate PNE.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] In game theory, a **cooperative** or **coalitional game** is a game with groups of players who form binding "coalitions" with external enforcement of cooperative behavior (e.g. through contract law).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] This is different from non-cooperative games in which there is either no possibility to forge alliances or all agreements need to be self-enforcing (e.g. through credible threats).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Cooperative games are analysed by focusing on coalitions that can be formed, and the joint actions that groups can take and the resulting collective payoffs.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] A cooperative game is given by specifying a value for every coalition.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Formally, the coalitional game consists of a finite set of players N , called the *grand coalition*, and a *characteristic function* $v:2^{N}\to \mathbb {R}$ from the set of all possible coalitions of players to a set of payments that satisfies $v(\emptyset )=0$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The function describes how much collective payoff a set of players can gain by forming a coalition.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Cooperative game theory is a branch of game theory that deals with the study of games where players can form coalitions, cooperate with one another, and make binding agreements.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The theory offers mathematical methods for analysing scenarios in which two or more players are required to make choices that will affect other players wellbeing.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Let $S\subsetneq N$ be a non-empty coalition of players.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] In other words, we simply restrict our attention to coalitions contained in S .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Subgames are useful because they allow us to apply solution concepts defined for the grand coalition on smaller coalitions.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Characteristic functions are often assumed to be superadditive (Owen 1995, p.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] $v(S\cup T)\geq v(S)+v(T)$ whenever $S,T\subseteq N$ satisfy $S\cap T=\emptyset$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] $S\subseteq T\Rightarrow v(S)\leq v(T)$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] This follows from superadditivity. i.e. if payoffs are normalized so singleton coalitions have zero value.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] A coalitional game v is considered **simple** if payoffs are either 1 or 0, i.e. coalitions are either "winning" or "losing".
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Equivalently, a **simple game** can be defined as a collection W of coalitions, where the members of W are called **winning** coalitions, and the others **losing** coalitions.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] It is sometimes assumed that a simple game is nonempty or that it does not contain an empty set.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] However, in other areas of mathematics, simple games are also called hypergraphs or Boolean functions (logic functions).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The restrictions that various axioms for simple games impose on their Nakamura number were also studied extensively.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] In particular, a computable simple game without a veto player has a Nakamura number greater than 3 only if it is a *proper* and *non-strong* game.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Let *G* be a strategic (non-cooperative) game.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Then, assuming that coalitions have the ability to enforce coordinated behaviour, there are several cooperative games associated with *G*.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] These games are often referred to as *representations of G*.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The main assumption in cooperative game theory is that the grand coalition N will form.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The challenge is then to allocate the payoff $v(N)$ among the players in some way.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Researchers have proposed different solution concepts based on different notions of fairness.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] An efficient payoff vector is called a *pre-imputation*, and an individually rational pre-imputation is called an imputation.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The stable set of a game (also known as the *von Neumann-Morgenstern solution* (von Neumann & Morgenstern 1944)) was the first solution proposed for games with more than 2 players.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Let v be a game and let x , y be two imputations of v .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Then x *dominates* y if some coalition $S\neq \emptyset$ satisfies $x_{i}>y_{i},\forall ~i\in S$ and $\sum _{i\in S}x_{i}\leq v(S)$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] In other words, players in S prefer the payoffs from x to those from y , and they can threaten to leave the grand coalition if y is used because the payoff they obtain on their own is at least as large as the allocation they receive under x .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Von Neumann and Morgenstern saw the stable set as the collection of acceptable behaviours in a society: None is clearly preferred to any other, but for each unacceptable behaviour there is a preferred alternative.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The definition is very general allowing the concept to be used in a wide variety of game formats.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] In words, the core is the set of imputations under which no coalition has a value greater than the sum of its members' payoffs.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Therefore, no coalition has incentive to leave the grand coalition and receive a larger payoff.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] For simple games, there is another notion of the core, when each player is assumed to have preferences on a set X of alternatives.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] A *profile* is a list $p=(\succ _{i}^{p})_{i\in N}$ of individual preferences $\succ _{i}^{p}$ on X .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Here $x\succ _{i}^{p}y$ means that individual i prefers alternative x to y at profile p .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Given a simple game v and a profile p , a *dominance* relation $\succ _{v}^{p}$ is defined on X by $x\succ _{v}^{p}y$ if and only if there is a winning coalition S (i.e., $v(S)=1$ ) satisfying $x\succ _{i}^{p}y$ for all $i\in S$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The *Nakamura number* of a simple game is the minimal number of winning coalitions with empty intersection.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] *Nakamura's theorem* states that the core $C(v,p)$ is nonempty for all profiles p of *acyclic* (alternatively, *transitive*) preferences if and only if X is finite *and* the cardinal number (the number of elements) of X is less than the Nakamura number of v .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] A variant by Kumabe and Mihara states that the core $C(v,p)$ is nonempty for all profiles p of preferences that have a *maximal element* if and only if the cardinal number of X is less than the Nakamura number of v .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Because the core may be empty, a generalization was introduced in (Shapley & Shubik 1966).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Clearly, regardless of whether the core is empty, the strong $\varepsilon$ -core will be non-empty for a large enough value of $\varepsilon$ and empty for a small enough (possibly negative) value of $\varepsilon$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Following this line of reasoning, the *least-core*, introduced in (Maschler, Peleg & Shapley 1979), is the intersection of all non-empty strong $\varepsilon$ -cores.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] It can also be viewed as the strong $\varepsilon$ -core for the smallest value of $\varepsilon$ that makes the set non-empty (Bilbao 2000).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The *Shapley value* is the unique payoff vector that is efficient, symmetric, and satisfies monotonicity.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] It was introduced by Lloyd Shapley (Shapley 1953) who showed that it is the unique payoff vector that is efficient, symmetric, additive, and assigns zero payoffs to dummy players.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The Shapley value of a superadditive game is individually rational, but this is not true in general.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Let $v:2^{N}\to \mathbb {R}$ be a game, and let $x\in \mathbb {R} ^{N}$ be an efficient payoff vector.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] the maximal amount player *i* can gain without the cooperation of player *j* by withdrawing from the grand coalition *N* under payoff vector *x*, assuming that the other players in *i'*s withdrawing coalition are satisfied with their payoffs under *x*.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The maximum surplus is a way to measure one player's bargaining power over another.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Intuitively, player *i* has more bargaining power than player *j* with respect to imputation *x* if $s_{ij}^{v}(x)>s_{ji}^{v}(x)$ , but player *j* is immune to player *i'*s threats if $x_{j}=v(j)$ , because he can obtain this payoff on his own.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The kernel contains all imputations where no player has this bargaining power over another.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] This solution concept was first introduced in (Davis & Maschler 1965).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The *Harsanyi dividend* (named after John Harsanyi, who used it to generalize the Shapley value in 1963) identifies the surplus that is created by a coalition of players in a cooperative game.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] To specify this surplus, the worth of this coalition is corrected by subtracting the surplus that was already created by subcoalitions.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] An explicit formula for the dividend is given by ${\textstyle d_{v}(S)=\sum _{T\subseteq S}(-1)^{|S\setminus T|}v(T)}$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The function $d_{v}:2^{N}\to \mathbb {R}$ is also known as the Möbius inverse of $v:2^{N}\to \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Indeed, we can recover v from $d_{v}$ by help of the formula ${\textstyle v(S)=d_{v}(S)+\sum _{T\subsetneq S}d_{v}(T)}$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Let $v:2^{N}\to \mathbb {R}$ be a game, and let $x\in \mathbb {R} ^{N}$ be a payoff vector.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The *excess* of x for a coalition $S\subseteq N$ is the quantity $v(S)-\sum _{i\in S}x_{i}$ ; that is, the gain that players in coalition S can obtain if they withdraw from the grand coalition N under payoff x and instead take the payoff $v(S)$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The *nucleolus* of v is the imputation for which the vector of excesses of all coalitions (a vector in $\mathbb {R} ^{2^{N}}$ ) is smallest in the leximin order.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The nucleolus was introduced in (Schmeidler 1969).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] (Maschler, Peleg & Shapley 1979) gave a more intuitive description: Starting with the least-core, record the coalitions for which the right-hand side of the inequality in the definition of $C_{\varepsilon }(v)$ cannot be further reduced without making the set empty.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Continue decreasing the right-hand side for the remaining coalitions, until it cannot be reduced without making the set empty.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Record the new set of coalitions for which the inequalities hold at equality; continue decreasing the right-hand side of remaining coalitions and repeat this process as many times as necessary until all coalitions have been recorded.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] The resulting payoff vector is the nucleolus.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Introduced by Shapley in (Shapley 1971), convex cooperative games capture the intuitive property some games have of "snowballing".
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] that is, "the incentives for joining a coalition increase as the coalition grows" (Shapley 1971), leading to the aforementioned snowball effect.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] For cost games, the inequalities are reversed, so that we say the cost game is *convex* if the characteristic function is submodular.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Submodular and supermodular set functions are also studied in combinatorial optimization.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Many of the results in (Shapley 1971) have analogues in (Edmonds 1970), where submodular functions were first presented as generalizations of matroids.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] In this context, the core of a convex cost game is called the *base polyhedron*, because its elements generalize base properties of matroids.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] However, the optimization community generally considers submodular functions to be the discrete analogues of convex functions (Lovász 1983), because the minimization of both types of functions is computationally tractable.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Unfortunately, this conflicts directly with Shapley's original definition of supermodular functions as "convex".
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] Corporate strategic decisions can develop and create value through cooperative game theory.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/cooperative-game-theory] This means that cooperative game theory can become the strategic theory of the firm, and different CGT solutions can simulate different institutions.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] In game theory, a game is said to be a **potential game** if the incentive of all players to change their strategy can be expressed using a single global function called the **potential function**.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] The concept originated in a 1996 paper by Dov Monderer and Lloyd Shapley.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] The properties of several types of potential games have since been studied.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Games can be either *ordinal* or *cardinal* potential games.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] In cardinal games, the difference in individual payoffs for each player from individually changing one's strategy, other things equal, has to have the same value as the difference in values for the potential function.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] In ordinal games, only the signs of the differences have to be the same.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] The potential function is a useful tool to analyze equilibrium properties of games, since the incentives of all players are mapped into one function, and the set of pure Nash equilibria can be found by locating the local optima of the potential function.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Convergence and finite-time convergence of an iterated game towards a Nash equilibrium can also be understood by studying the potential function.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Potential games can be studied as repeated games with state so that every round played has a direct consequence on game's state in the next round.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] This approach has applications in distributed control such as distributed resource allocation, where players without a central correlation mechanism can cooperate to achieve a globally optimal resource distribution.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Let N be the number of players, A the set of action profiles over the action sets $A_{i}$ of each player and $u_{i}:A\to \mathbb {R}$ be the payoff function for player $1\leq i\leq N$ .
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] equals the change in the utility of that player.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] equals the change in the player's utility, times a positive player-specific weight.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] of the change in the player's utility, whereas the magnitude of change may differ.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] That is: when a player switches action, if the player's utility increases, then the potential increases (but the opposite is not necessarily true).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Every ordinal PF is a generalized-ordinal PF.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] , maximizing the common potential function leads to the same outcome as maximizing his own utility.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Note that while there are N utility functions, one for each player, there is only one potential function.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Thus, through the lens of potential functions, the players become interchangeable (in the sense of one of the definitions above).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Because of this *symmetry* of the game, decentralized algorithms based on the shared potential function often lead to convergence (in some of sense) to a Nash equilibria.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] In *a* 2-player, 2-action game with externalities, individual players' payoffs are given by the function *u**i*(*a**i*, *a**j*) = *b**i* *a**i* + *w* *a**i* *a**j*, where *a**i* is players i's action, *a**j* is the opponent's action, and *w* is *a* positive externality from choosing the same action.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] The action choices are +1 and −1, as seen in the payoff matrix in Figure 1.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] The solution for player 2 is equivalent.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Using numerical values *b*1 = 2, *b*2 = −1, *w* = 3, this example transforms into *a* simple battle of the sexes, as shown in Figure 2.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] The game has two pure Nash equilibria, (+1, +1) and (−1, −1).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] These are also the local maxima of the potential function (Figure 3).
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] The only stochastically stable equilibrium is (+1, +1), the global maximum of the potential function.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Exact potential games are equivalent to congestion games: Rosenthal proved that every congestion game has an exact potential; Monderer and Shapley proved the opposite direction: every game with an exact potential function is a congestion game.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] The class of *ordinal* potential games is much larger.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Fabrikant, Papadimitriou and Talwar proved that, for every problem in the complexity class PLS (essentially, every local search problem), there exists an ordinal potential game with polynomially many players, such that the set of pure Nash equilibria equals the set of local optima.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] An **improvement path** (also called **Nash dynamics**) is a sequence of strategy-vectors, in which each vector is attained from the previous vector by a single player switching his strategy to a strategy that strictly increases his utility.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] If a game has a generalized-ordinal-potential function $\Phi$ , then $\Phi$ is strictly increasing in every improvement path, so every improvement path is acyclic.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] If, in addition, the game has finitely many strategies, then every improvement path must be finite.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] This property is called the **finite improvement property (FIP)**.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] We have just proved that every finite generalized-ordinal-potential game has the FIP.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] The opposite is also true: every finite game has the FIP has a generalized-ordinal-potential function.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] The terminal state in every finite improvement path is a Nash equilibrium, so FIP implies the existence of a pure-strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Moreover, it implies that a Nash equilibrium can be computed by a distributed process, in which each agent only has to improve his own strategy.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] A **best-response path** is a special case of an improvement path, in which each vector is attained from the previous vector by a single player switching his strategy to a best-response strategy.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] The property that every best-response path is finite is called the **finite best-response property (FBRP)**.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] FBRP is weaker than FIP, and it still implies the existence of a pure-strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] It also implies that a Nash equilibrium can be computed by a distributed process, but the computational burden on the agents is higher than with FIP, since they have to compute a best-response.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] An even weaker property is **weak-acyclicity (WA)**.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] It means that, for any initial strategy-vector, *there exists* a finite best-response path starting at that vector.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Weak-acyclicity is not sufficient for existence of a potential function (since some improvement-paths may be cyclic), but it is sufficient for the existence of pure-strategy Nash equilibrium.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] It implies that a Nash equilibrium can be computed almost-surely by a stochastic distributed process, in which at each point, a player is chosen at random, and this player chooses a best-strategy at random.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] Abraham Neyman studied potential games in which (a) the potential is a smooth and concave function, (b) the strategy sets are convex, (c) the utilities are bounded.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] He proves that, in such games, any correlated equilibrium is a mixture of pure strategy profiles which maximize the potential.
[src:algorithmic-game-theory/potential-game] If, in addition, (d) the strategy sets are compact, (e) the potential is a strictly concave function, then the correlated equilibrium is unique.
